SIMPLE: this
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: This
<hw>This</hw> <pr>(⟦th⟧⟦icr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>pron. & a.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>These</plw> <pr>(⟦th⟧⟦emac⟧z)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[OE. <ets>this</ets>, <ets>thes</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦edh⟧⟦emac⟧s</ets>,
masc., <ets>⟦edh⟧e⟦oacute⟧s</ets>, fem., <ets>⟦edh⟧is</ets>, neut.; akin
to OS. <ets>these</ets>, D. <ets>deze</ets>, G. <ets>dieser</ets>, OHG.
<ets>diser</ets>, <ets>deser</ets>, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧essi</ets>;
originally from the definite article + a particle <ets>-se</ets>,
<ets>-si</ets>; cf. Goth. <ets>sai</ets> behold. See <er>The</er>,
<er>That</er>, and cf. <er>These</er>, <er>Those</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>As a demonstrative pronoun, <xex>this</xex> denotes
something that is present or near in place or time, or something just
mentioned, or that is just about to be mentioned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When they heard <qex>this</qex>, they were pricked in their
heart.</q> <rj><qau>Acts ii. 37.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But know <qex>this</qex>, that if the good man of the house had
known in what watch the thief would come, he would have watched.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xxiv. 43.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>As an adjective, <xex>this</xex> has the same
demonstrative force as the pronoun, but is followed by a noun; <as>as,
<ex>this</ex> book; <ex>this</ex> way to town</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>This</xex> may be used as opposed or correlative to
<xex>that</xex>, and sometimes as opposed to <xex>other</xex> or to a
second <xex>this</xex>. See the Note under <er>That</er>, 1.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>This</qex> way and <qex>that</qex> wavering sails they
bend.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A body of <qex>this</qex> or <qex>that</qex> denomination is
produced.</q> <rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their judgment in <qex>this</qex> we may not, and in
<qex>that</qex> we need not, follow.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Consider the arguments which the author had to write
<qex>this</qex>, or to design the <qex>other</qex>, before you arraign
him.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy crimes . . . soon by <qex>this</qex> or <qex>this</qex> will
end.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>This</xex>, like <xex>a</xex>, <xex>every</xex>,
<xex>that</xex>, etc., may refer to a number, as of years, persons,
etc., taken collectively or as a whole.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>This</qex> twenty years have I been with thee..</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xxxi. 38.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have not wept <qex>this</qex> years; but now⟦br⟧
My mother comes afresh into my eyes.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thistle</ent>⟦br⟧
